11:22.340 --> 11:29.100
There is a fundamental energy balance equation that every single surface on Earth has to satisfy.

11:29.320 --> 11:30.620
Every single surface.

11:30.780 --> 11:32.660
Okay. Lay the equation out for us.

11:33.000 --> 11:41.900
When solar energy hits a surface, the net radiation, let's call it R sub n, must equal the sum of three distinct pathways.

11:42.320 --> 11:44.680
Okay. R sub n equals three pathways.

11:44.920 --> 11:45.360
What are they?

11:45.360 --> 11:49.120
Ground heat flux, sensible heat flux, and latent heat flux.

11:49.600 --> 11:54.040
So the sun comes in and has to lead through one of those three doors.

11:54.180 --> 11:55.760
Three doors. I like that visualization.

11:56.160 --> 11:56.940
Let's walk through them.

11:57.000 --> 11:57.880
What is the first door?

11:58.220 --> 12:01.000
The first door is the ground heat flux, or G.

12:01.520 --> 12:02.740
This is conductive heat.

12:03.420 --> 12:11.500
It is the thermal energy bleeding directly down, molecule by molecule, through the roof material and into the interior of the building.

12:11.500 --> 12:19.500
Oh, man. Which means the building starts baking, and the occupants inside immediately crank up the air conditioning to fight it.

12:19.680 --> 12:21.100
Exactly. That's door number one.

12:21.560 --> 12:24.480
The second door is the sensible heat flux, H.

12:24.700 --> 12:25.420
Sensible heat.

12:25.700 --> 12:26.040
Right.

12:26.780 --> 12:32.160
This is the heat radiating off the exterior surface and directly warming the surrounding air.

12:32.280 --> 12:34.480
Like when you stand in a parking lot in July.

12:34.480 --> 12:46.820
Yes. If you've ever stood in an asphalt parking lot in the middle of summer and seen the air visibly shimmering and distorting above the ground, you are looking at sensible heat.

12:47.080 --> 12:51.280
And that's the mechanism driving the urban heat island effect, isn't it?

12:51.860 --> 12:58.920
Millions of square feet of black tar acting as radiators, turning the city into a convection oven.

12:58.920 --> 13:00.080
A literal oven.

13:00.280 --> 13:00.460
Yeah.

13:00.520 --> 13:05.000
Now, the third door is the critical one. Latent heat flux, or LV.

13:05.540 --> 13:07.820
Latent heat. What happens at this door?

13:08.060 --> 13:11.460
This is the energy consumed by evapotranspiration.

13:12.460 --> 13:22.140
When water transitions from a liquid state into a gaseous vapor state, it requires a tremendous amount of energy to break those molecular bonds.

13:22.420 --> 13:22.780
Okay.

13:23.020 --> 13:27.780
So it consumes that thermal energy without raising the temperature of the surrounding air.

13:27.780 --> 13:30.280
Wait, without raising the temperature? That's huge.

13:30.840 --> 13:35.560
But if I'm an inert flat roof, I have zero water and zero vegetation.

13:36.140 --> 13:38.300
So you have entirely boarded up that third door.

13:38.520 --> 13:40.400
I force latent heat to zero.

13:40.800 --> 13:50.160
Exactly. And because the total equation still has to balance, 100% of that incoming solar radiation is crammed through the first two doors.

13:50.640 --> 13:53.200
It all becomes ground heat and sensible heat.

13:53.200 --> 14:01.040
Yep. The amount of destructive thermal energy you export to the FITI scales linearly with how big your roof is.

14:01.120 --> 14:12.400
That is terrifying. But when you populate the Phi sub T channel, when you install a living roof, the evapotranspiration suddenly becomes the dominant discharge pathway.

14:12.400 --> 14:14.760
The thermodynamics completely invert.

