Turning liquid water into vapor consumes roughly 2.45 megajoules per kilogram of water.

14:27.520 --> 14:32.360
2.45 megajoules per kilogram? Let's visualize that for a second.

14:32.500 --> 14:34.120
Please do, because it's a massive number.

14:34.120 --> 14:40.800
A single megajoules is roughly the kinetic energy of a one-ton vehicle moving at 100 miles per hour.

14:40.960 --> 14:41.360
Wow.

14:41.560 --> 14:51.060
Right. So a living roof is pulling multiple megajoules of energy out of the incoming solar assault for every single liter of water it breathes out into the sky.

14:51.240 --> 14:56.440
It is performing a massive, silent, molecular judo throw on the sun's energy.

14:56.840 --> 14:59.440
A molecular judo throw. I love that.

14:59.440 --> 15:06.720
And because the energy is consumed in the phase change, it vanishes from the sensible heat cycle.

15:07.180 --> 15:10.140
It vanishes. It's actively refrigerating the boundary layer.

15:10.300 --> 15:13.920
How much of a difference does that actually make, temperature-wise?

15:14.420 --> 15:24.420
Measured ambient temperatures above densely vegetated living roofs can drop by up to 4 degrees Celsius compared to adjacent bare roofs.

15:24.680 --> 15:28.460
4 degrees Celsius. That's over 7 degrees Fahrenheit.

15:28.460 --> 15:32.780
That's the difference between a hot day and a dangerous heat wave.

15:32.880 --> 15:40.800
Exactly. The interface is shifting the energy away from destabilizing ambient heat into thermally neutral latent heat.

